{
  "@context": "https://www.openphar.org/ontology/context/pharmacopoeia.jsonld",
  "@id": "https://www.openphar.org/data/jp/minerals/purified-sodium-hyaluronate",
  "@type": "MineralSubstanceMonograph",
  "prefLabel": {
    "en": "Purified Sodium Hyaluronate",
    "ja": "精製ヒアルロン酸ナトリウム"
  },
  "monographId": "JP18-purified-sodium-hyaluronate",
  "publisher": "JP",
  "status": "Official",
  "version": "18",
  "definition": {
    "en": "Purified Sodium Hyaluronate is the sodium salt of glycosaminoglycans composed of disaccharide units of D-glucuronic acid and N-acetyl-D-glucosamine ob-tained from cockscomb or microorganisms. It contains not less than 90."
  },
  "appearance": {
    "en": "Purified Sodium Hyaluronate occurs as white, powder, granules or fibrous masses. It is sparingly soluble in water, and practically insoluble in ethanol (99.5). It is hygroscopic."
  },
  "testSpecification": [
    {
      "@type": "IdentificationSpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Identification"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Identification",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(1) Determine the infrared absorption spec-trum of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate, previously dried, as directed in the potassium bromide disk method under In-frared Spectrophotometry <2.25>, and compare the spectrum with the Reference Spectrum: both spectra exhibit similar in-tensities of absorption at the same wave numbers. (2) A solution of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate (1 in 1000) responds to Qualitative Tests <1.09> (1) for sodium salt. Viscosity <2.53> Weigh accurately an amount of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate so that the downflowing time of its so-lution in 100 mL of 0.2 mol/L sodium chloride TS is 2.0 to 2.4 times longer than that of 0.2 mol/L sodium chloride TS, dissolve in 0.2 mol/L sodium chloride TS to make exactly 100 mL, and use this solution as the sample solution (1). Pipet 16 mL, 12 mL and 8 mL of the sample solution (1), to each add 0.2 mol/L sodium chloride TS to make exactly 20 mL, and use these solutions as the sample solutions (2), (3) and (4), respectively. Perform the test with the sample solu-tions (1), (2), (3) and (4) as directed under Method 1 at 30 ± 0.19C using an Ubbelohde-type viscometer in which the downflowing time for 0.2 mol/L sodium chloride TS is 200 to 300 seconds: the intrinsic viscosity calculated on the dried basis is between 10.0 dL/g and 24.9 dL/g or between 25.0 dL/g and 55.0 dL/g."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "PuritySpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Purity"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Purity",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(1) Clarity and color of solution—Dissolve 0.10 g of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate in 10 mL of water: the solu-tion is clear and colorless. Chloride <1.03>—Dissolve 0.20 g of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate in 15 mL of water, add 6 mL of dilute nitric acid, and heat on a water bath for 30 minutes. After cooling, add water to make 50 mL. Perform the test using this solu-tion as the test solution. Prepare the control solution with 0.70 mL of 0.01 mol/L hydrochloric acid VS (not more than 0.124z). Heavy metals <1.07>—Proceed with 1.0 g of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate according to Method 2, and perform the test. Prepare the control solution with 2.0 mL of Stand-ard Lead Solution (not more than 20 ppm). Protein—Weigh accurately about 20 mg of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate, calculated on the dried basis, dissolve in 1.0 mL of dilute sodium hydroxide TS, and use this solu-tion as the sample solution. Separately, weigh accurately about 10 mg of bovine serum albumin, dissolve in dilute so- (C14 H20NNaO 11)n dium hydroxide TS to make exactly 1000 mL, and use this solution as the standard solution. To 1.0 mL each of the [9067-32-7] Purified Sodium Hyaluronate is the sodium salt of glycosaminoglycans composed of disaccharide units of D-glucuronic acid and N-acetyl-D-glucosamine ob-tained from cockscomb or microorganisms. It contains not less than 90.0z and not more than 105.5z of sodium hyaluronate [(C H NNaO ) ], sample solution and standard solution add 5.0 mL of alka-line copper TS (2), immediately stir, allow to stand at room temperature for 10 minutes, add 0.5 mL of diluted Folin's TS (1 in 2), immediately stir, and allow to stand at room temperature for 30 minutes. Perform the test with these solu-tions as directed under Ultraviolet-visible Spectrophotome-try <2.24>, using a solution, prepared with 1.0 mL of dilute calculated on the dried basis. 14 20 n sodium hydrochloride in the same manner, as the blank: the absorbance of the sample solution at 750 nm does not exceed It is composed of an average molecular mass of the sodium salt of hyaluronic acid between 500,000 and 1,490,000 or between 1,500,000 and 3,900,000. The average molecular mass of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate should be labeled. the absorbance of the standard solution (not more than 0.05z). Nucleic acid—Determine the absorbance of a solu-tion of 0.10 g Purified Sodium Hyaluronate in 50 mL of water as directed under Ultraviolet-visible Spectrophotome- ‌try <2.24>, using water as the blank: the absorbance at 260 nm is not more than 0.02. Other acidic mucopolysaccharides—(In the case of chicken-derived samples) Dissolve 0.25 g of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate in 100 mL of water, and use this solution as the sample solution. Immerse a cellulose acetate membrane 6 cm in length in 0.2 mol/L pyridine-formic acid buffer solution (pH 3.0). Take out the membrane and remove excessive buffer solution using a filter paper. Place the membrane in an electrophoresis vessel saturated with 0.2 mol/L pyridine-formic acid buffer solution (pH 3.0) and run at 0.5 mA/cm for 1 minute. Apply 2 mL of the sample solution to the mem-brane in an area 1 cm in width at 1.5 cm from the anode. Carry out electrophoresis at 0.5 mA/cm for 1 hour. After the electrophoresis, stain the membrane by immersing it in alcian blue staining solution for 10 to 20 minutes. After staining, decolorize sufficiently with diluted acetic acid (100) (3 in 100): no bands other than the principal band appears. Hemolytic streptococci—(In the case of microor-ganism-derived samples) Dissolve 0.5 g of Purified Sodium"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "AssaySpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Assay"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Assay",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "Weigh accurately about 50 mg of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate, and dissolve in water to make exactly 50 mL. Pipet 1 mL of this solution, add water to make exactly 20 mL, and use this solution as the sample solution. Separately, weigh accurately about 20 mg of D-Glucuronolactone RS, previously dried (under reduced pressure not exceeding 0.67 kPa, silica gel, 24 hours), and dissolve in water to make ex-actly 100 mL. Pipet 1 mL of this solution, add water to make exactly 10 mL, and use this solution as the standard solution. Pipet 1 mL each of the sample solution and standard solu-tion, gently add into the 5.0 mL of sodium tetraborate-sulfuric acid TS, previously cooled in ice water, stir while cooling, heat in a water bath for 10 minutes, and cool in ice water. To each solution add exactly 0.2 mL of carbazole TS, stir well, heat in a water bath for 15 minutes, and cool in ice water to room temperature. Determine the absorbances, AT and AS, of the sample solution and standard solution at 530 nm as directed under Ultraviolet-visible Spectrophotometry <2.24>, using a solution, prepared with 1 mL of water in the same manner, as the blank. Hyaluronate in sterile isotonic sodium chloride solution to make exactly 100 mL. Take 0.5 mL of this solution, apply to 2 blood agar plates, respectively, using a Conradi stick, and Amount (mg) of sodium hyaluronate [(C ＝ MS × AT/AS × 2.279 14H 20NNaO 11)n] incubate at 379C for 48 hours: no hemolytic colonies appear, or if any, no streptococci are observed in the colony under a microscope. Hemolysis—(In the case of microorganism-derived samples) Dissolve 0.40 g of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate in sterile isotonic sodium chloride solution to make exactly 100 mL. To 0.5 mL of this solution add 0.5 mL of 1z blood sus-pension, mix, allow to stand at 379C for 2 hours, and, if nec-essary, centrifuge at 3000 revolutions per minute for 10 minutes: the erythrocytes precipitate and the supernatant liq-uid is clear as in a blank determination performed in the same manner using 0.5 mL of sterile isotonic sodium chlo-ride solution as the blank and 0.5 mL of sterile purified water as the positive control. Loss on drying <2.41> Not more than 15.0z (0.1 g, reduced pressure not exceeding 0.67 kPa, phosphorus (V) oxide, 609C, 5 hours). Microbial limit <4.05> The acceptance criteria of TAMC and TYMC are 102 CFU/g and 101 CFU/g, respectively. In the case of the sample of the labeled average molecular mass between 500,000 and 1,490,000, perform the test with 1 g, and of the labeled average molecular mass between 1,500,000 and 3,900,000, perform the test with 0.3 g. Average molecular mass In the case of the labeled average molecular mass of between 500,000 and 1,490,000. Calculate the average molecular mass of Purified Sodium Hyaluronate according to the following equation: it is be-tween 500,000 and 1,490,000. For [h], use the maximum vis-cosity under Viscosity. Ø[h] × 105 »  1    MS: Amount (mg) of D-Glucuronolactone RS taken"
      }
    }
  ],
  "storageConditions": {
    "en": "Containers—Tight containers. Storage—Light-resistant, at not exceeding 159C."
  }
